      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk 3.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes (FDA in-house, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) operate under documented software quality assurance plans including version control, regression testing, and change management procedures consistent with Gradation 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Benchmark problems and analytical solutions have been used to verify the numerical implementation of each code. Results agree within accepted tolerances for linear static structural analyses."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence studies were performed on the pedicle screw-rod construct geometry. Peak von Mises stress in the screw neck varied by less than 3% between the medium and fine meshes, satisfying Gradation 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Direct sparse solvers with double-precision arithmetic were employed. Residual norms confirmed convergence to machine precision; iterative solver alternatives were checked and produced equivalent results."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Model setup procedures were documented in standard operating procedures and independently reviewed by a second analyst at each participating laboratory. No discrepancies were identified in boundary condition or material assignment."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level of 3 given model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic continuum mechanics with frictional contact was selected as the model form. Assumptions of small deformation and isotropic material behavior are justified by the ASTM F1717 test regime, which remains below yield. Sensitivity analyses confirm that the chosen model form is appropriate for the quantities of interest."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus, yield strength) were sourced from ASTM F136 and confirmed by coupon testing of the specific lot. Geometric inputs were derived from CMM measurements of the actual test specimens. Uncertainty in inputs was characterized and propagated."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories, providing adequate sample size for statistical characterization of experimental variability consistent with Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level; shortfall documented with impact assessment.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single axial compressive load level per ASTM F1717. While this satisfies the standard protocol, only one test condition was evaluated, limiting coverage of the loading envelope. This shortfall below the required Gradation 3 is documented; its impact on overall credibility is judged acceptable given the well-characterized single-condition nature of the regulatory submission."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Specimen-specific FEA models were constructed using CMM-measured geometry and lot-specific material data. Fixture compliance was characterized and incorporated. The mapping between experimental inputs and model inputs was verified by an independent reviewer."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "Predicted construct stiffness and peak rod stress were compared against experimental measurements using quantitative metrics including MAPE and 95% prediction intervals. Agreement was within 8% for stiffness and 11% for stress, satisfying Gradation 3 criteria."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "The quantities of interest — construct stiffness and maximum principal stress in the screw neck — are directly linked to the fatigue failure mode addressed in the regulatory submission. Their clinical and mechanical relevance is well established in the spinal implant literature."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity replicates the ASTM F1717 test configuration used in the intended regulatory submission. Geometry, loading mode, and boundary conditions are representative of the intended use. The ensemble approach across three independent modeling teams strengthens confidence in the validation conclusions."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Overall credibility is assessed as sufficient for the intended regulatory submission. Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 factors meet or exceed required levels. The single shortfall in Test conditions (achieved Gradation 2 vs. required Gradation 3) is judged acceptable given the single-condition nature of the ASTM F1717 protocol and the robustness demonstrated across the multi-team FEA ensemble. The model has been applied in clinical research contexts and the ensemble approach provides additional confidence. Decision: Accepted.",
